---
title: Quick Start
description: Launch NodeDB and run your first queries in under 5 minutes.
---

# Quick Start

This guide takes you from zero to running multi-modal queries in under 5 minutes.

## 1. Start NodeDB

NodeDB works without a configuration file. Start it with defaults:

```bash
# From the repository root
./target/release/nodedb
```

You should see output like:

```
2026-03-23T10:00:00Z INFO nodedb: Starting NodeDB 0.1.0
2026-03-23T10:00:00Z INFO nodedb: Listening on 127.0.0.1:6433 (native)
2026-03-23T10:00:00Z INFO nodedb: Listening on 127.0.0.1:6432 (PostgreSQL)
2026-03-23T10:00:00Z INFO nodedb: Listening on 127.0.0.1:6480 (HTTP)
2026-03-23T10:00:00Z INFO nodedb: Data directory: ~/.local/share/nodedb/
2026-03-23T10:00:00Z INFO nodedb: Data Plane cores: 7
2026-03-23T10:00:00Z INFO nodedb: Memory limit: 8 GB
```

The server is now ready. Leave this terminal running and open another.

## 2. Connect via PostgreSQL

In another terminal, connect using `psql` (the PostgreSQL command-line client):

```bash
psql -h 127.0.0.1 -p 6432
```

Or if you prefer to skip entering a password:

```bash
psql -h 127.0.0.1 -p 6432 --no-password
```

You'll see the NodeDB prompt:

```
psql (15.0, server NodeDB/0.1.0)
Type "help" for help.

nodedb=#
```

## 3. Create a Collection

Collections are NodeDB's flexible schema containers. Create one:

```sql
nodedb=# CREATE COLLECTION documents;
CREATE COLLECTION
```

## 4. Insert Documents

Insert documents with mixed field types:

```sql
nodedb=# INSERT INTO documents (id, title, content)
VALUES
  (1, 'AI Safety', 'Alignment research for AGI systems'),
  (2, 'Vector DBs', 'Semantic search using embeddings');
INSERT 2
```

Query back:

```sql
nodedb=# SELECT id, title FROM documents;
 id |    title
----+-------------
  1 | AI Safety
  2 | Vector DBs
(2 rows)
```

## 5. Insert Vectors

Add an embedding field and search by vector similarity:

```sql
-- Insert a document with an embedding (384-dimensional vector)
nodedb=# INSERT INTO documents (id, title, embedding)
VALUES (3, 'Machine Learning',
  ARRAY[0.1, 0.2, 0.3, /* ... 381 more values ... */]);
INSERT 1
```

Search for similar documents:

```sql
nodedb=# SELECT id, title,
  vector_distance(embedding, ARRAY[0.09, 0.21, 0.29, /* ... */]) as distance
FROM documents
WHERE embedding IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY distance
LIMIT 5;

 id |       title        | distance
----+--------------------+----------
  3 | Machine Learning   |     0.02
(1 row)
```

## 6. Create a Vector Index

For fast similarity search, create an HNSW index:

```sql
nodedb=# CREATE VECTOR INDEX idx_embeddings
  ON documents (embedding)
  METRIC cosine
  M 16
  EF_CONSTRUCTION 200;
CREATE VECTOR INDEX
```

Now vector searches automatically use the index. You can search with 10M-scale embeddings in milliseconds.

## 7. Insert Graph Edges

NodeDB has a native Graph engine. Insert nodes and edges:

```sql
-- Create edges (node_id, related_id, edge_type, weight)
nodedb=# INSERT INTO edges (source, target, relation_type, weight)
VALUES
  (1, 2, 'related', 0.8),
  (2, 3, 'related', 0.9),
  (1, 3, 'derived', 0.6);
INSERT 3
```

Traverse the graph:

```sql
nodedb=# SELECT * FROM graph_traverse(1, 'relation_type', 2);
 node_id | hop | distance
---------+-----+----------
       1 |   0 |        0
       2 |   1 |     0.80
       3 |   2 |     0.71
(3 rows)
```

## 8. Add CRDT State

NodeDB's CRDT engine powers collaborative editing and offline sync:

```sql
-- Insert collaborative state (version, actor_id, data)
nodedb=# INSERT INTO collaborative_state (doc_id, actor_id, vector_clock, data)
VALUES (1, 'client-1', '{"actor-1": 5}',
  '{"title": "Updated AI Safety", "edits": 5}');
INSERT 1
```

## 9. Insert Timeseries Data

Log metrics and events:

```sql
nodedb=# INSERT INTO metrics (timestamp, metric_name, value, labels)
VALUES
  ('2026-03-23T10:00:00Z', 'query_latency_ms', 42, '{"endpoint": "/vector-search"}'),
  ('2026-03-23T10:00:01Z', 'query_latency_ms', 38, '{"endpoint": "/vector-search"}');
INSERT 2
```

Query with time range:

```sql
nodedb=# SELECT metric_name, AVG(value) as avg_latency, COUNT(*) as count
FROM metrics
WHERE timestamp >= '2026-03-23T10:00:00Z'
  AND metric_name = 'query_latency_ms'
GROUP BY metric_name;

  metric_name      | avg_latency | count
-------------------+-------------+-------
 query_latency_ms  |          40 |     2
(1 row)
```

## 10. Use the HTTP API

NodeDB also exposes a REST API on port 6480. In another terminal:

```bash
# Execute a SQL query
curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:6480/query \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"sql": "SELECT id, title FROM documents LIMIT 5"}'
```

Response:

```json
{
  "columns": ["id", "title"],
  "rows": [
    [1, "AI Safety"],
    [2, "Vector DBs"],
    [3, "Machine Learning"]
  ],
  "latency_ms": 2.5
}
```

## 11. Check Collections and Schemas

View your collections and their schemas:

```sql
nodedb=# SHOW COLLECTIONS;
    collection
-----------------
 documents
 edges
 collaborative_state
 metrics
(4 rows)

nodedb=# DESCRIBE documents;
    name    |  type   | indexed
-------------+---------+---------
 id          | integer | yes
 title       | text    | no
 content     | text    | no
 embedding   | vector  | yes
(4 rows)
```

## 12. Clean Up

When done, exit psql:

```sql
nodedb=# \q
```

Stop the server with Ctrl+C in the terminal where you started it.

## What's Next?

You've now seen NodeDB's six engines in action: vector search, graph traversal, documents, metadata queries, collaborative state, and timeseries.

